posts.title: Timmehtek – misc
posts.content:
From Silas Gallardo:
“I always believed that one of tim goddard’s most timeless videos is this one. not to say his recent minis aren’t amazing, but misc has such a great mix of tim’s unique style, great length for what the video is worth full of inspiration, and one key element of the video in my opinion; it has such a wide variety of manipulations full of useful transitions. it’s added a lot to my understanding of poi, also because it’s accessible.”

mmm yes. Truly masterful work by a master.

posts.title: Poi Hardware Factsheet
posts.content:
Handle Weights
Delphin Club Knob (drilled for poi):            3.8g
Radical Fish Club Knob (drilled for poi):       4.6g
Play PX3 Club Knob:                     10.5g
Lanternsmith Pom Grips (0 washers):     16g
3/4” Rubber Chair Stopper:                      24g
Play Silicone Poi Knob:                         31.2g
Lanternsmith Pom Grips (+6 washers):    33g

Poi-head Weights

Glowstick:                               20g
Flowlight (no flowmas)          54g
Flowmass                        30g
Flowlight (+1 Flowmass)                 84g
Flowlight (+2 Flowmass)                 114g
Pod poi –                               128g
80mm Contact Ball –                     130g
Pod Poi (+1 Flowmass) –                 158g
90mm Play Contact Ball –                180g
100mm Play Contact Ball –               200g
3″ supreme foreheads –          195g
Trick Concepts Xtreme Poi               250g

US Standard –> Metric Conversions (for tether width)
3/16” / .1875”                          4.7mm
1/4” / .25″                                     6.3mm
5/16” / .3125″                          8mm
7/16” / .4375″                          11.1mm
1/2” / .5″                                      12.7mm

posts.title: Antiphon
posts.content:
Keith is one of the first to take his poi and make them ridiculously long, using his poi almost entirely as a new object with new abilities to wrap fully around different body spaces. He’s a well of good ideas and thrives on eccentricity and mastery. His style is rough and snappy, a testament to his roots in flow as a metal drummer. He also doesn’t have dreadlocks anymore. Normally I’d link to his youtube channel, but he’s so cool he doesn’t have one.
